# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batteryless-radio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The voltage and frequency of electric power differs between regions.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In much of the world, a voltage (nominally) of 230 volts and frequency of 50 Hz is used.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In North America, the most common combination is 120 V and a frequency of 60 Hz.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Other combinations exist, for example, 230 V at 60 Hz.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Travellers' portable appliances may be inoperative or damaged by foreign electrical supplies.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Non-interchangeable plugs and sockets in different regions provide some protection from accidental use of appliances with incompatible voltage and frequency requirements.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In the US, the electricity that a building receives is called an electrical service, and what comes out of a receptacle is referred to by its voltage, such as 120 or 240.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Sometimes it might be referred to by its number of phases, such as Three Phase.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In the UK, mains electric power is generally referred to as "the mains".
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] More than half of power in Canada is hydroelectricity, and mains electricity is often referred to as "hydro" in some regions of the country.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] This is also reflected in names of current and historical electricity utilities such as Hydro-Québec, BC Hydro, Manitoba Hydro, Hydro One (Ontario), and Newfoundland and Labrador Hydro.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Worldwide, many different mains power systems are found for the operation of household and light commercial electrical appliances and lighting.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] All of these parameters vary among regions.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The voltages are generally in the range 100–240 V (always expressed as root-mean-square voltage).
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The two commonly used frequencies are 50 Hz and 60 Hz.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Single-phase or three-phase power is most commonly used today, although two-phase systems were used early in the 20th century.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Foreign enclaves, such as large industrial plants or overseas military bases, may have a different standard voltage or frequency from the surrounding areas.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Some city areas may use standards different from that of the surrounding countryside (e.g. in Libya).
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Regions in an effective state of anarchy may have no central electrical authority, with electric power provided by incompatible private sources.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Many other combinations of voltage and utility frequency were formerly used, with frequencies between 25 Hz and 133 Hz and voltages from 100 V to 250 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Direct current (DC) has been displaced by alternating current (AC) in public power systems, but DC was used especially in some city areas to the end of the 20th century.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The modern combinations of 230 V/50 Hz and 120 V/60 Hz, listed in IEC 60038, did not apply in the first few decades of the 20th century and are still not universal.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Industrial plants with three-phase power will have different, higher voltages installed for large equipment (and different sockets and plugs), but the common voltages listed here would still be found for lighting and portable equipment.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Electricity is used for lighting, heating, cooling, electric motors and electronic equipment.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Includes televisions, set-top boxes, home theatre systems, DVD players, and video game consoles.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Includes desktop and laptop computers, monitors, and networking equipment.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Includes small electric devices, heating elements, exterior lights, outdoor grills, pool and spa heaters, backup electricity generators, and motors not listed above.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Does not include electric vehicle charging.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Electronic appliances such as computers or televisions sets typically use an AC to DC converter or AC adapter to power the device.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] This is often capable of operation with a wide range of voltage and with both common power frequencies.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Other AC applications usually have much more restricted input ranges.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Portable appliances use single-phase electric power, with two or three wired contacts at each outlet.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Two wires (neutral and live/active/hot) carry current to operate the device.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] A third wire, not always present, connects conductive parts of the appliance case to earth ground.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] This protects users from electric shock if live internal parts accidentally contact the case.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In northern and central Europe, residential electrical supply is commonly 400 V three-phase electric power, which gives 230 V between any single phase and neutral; house wiring may be a mix of three-phase and single-phase circuits, but three-phase residential use is rare in the UK.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] High-power appliances such as kitchen stoves, water heaters and household power heavy tools like log splitters may be supplied from the 400 V three-phase power supply.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Small portable electrical equipment is connected to the power supply through flexible cables terminated in a plug, which is inserted into a fixed receptacle (socket).
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Larger household electrical equipment and industrial equipment may be permanently wired to the fixed wiring of the building.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] For example, in North American homes a window-mounted self-contained air conditioner unit would be connected to a wall plug, whereas the central air conditioning for a whole home would be permanently wired.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Larger plug and socket combinations are used for industrial equipment carrying larger currents, higher voltages, or three phase electric power.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Circuit breakers and fuses are used to detect short circuits between the line and neutral or ground wires or the drawing of more current than the wires are rated to handle (overload protection) to prevent overheating and possible fire.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] These protective devices are usually mounted in a central panel—most commonly a distribution board or consumer unit—in a building, but some wiring systems also provide a protection device at the socket or within the plug.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Residual-current devices, also known as ground-fault circuit interrupters and appliance leakage current interrupters, are used to detect *ground faults*—flow of current in other than the neutral and line wires (like the ground wire or a person).
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] When a ground fault is detected, the device quickly cuts off the circuit.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The terms "ground wires" and "earth wires" are used interchangeably, depending on regional differences, for a wire that connects to the earth or some conducting body that serves in place of the earth to take the electrical discharge.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Grounding wires are installed as a safety feature in order to route electricity into another safe body that is not electrically conductive like the air or ground in order to prevent short circuits or electrocution.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Most of the world population (Europe, Africa, Asia, Australia, New Zealand, and much of South America) use a supply that is within 6% of 230 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In the United Kingdom the nominal supply voltage is 230 V +10%/−6% to accommodate the fact that most transformers are in fact still set to 240 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The 230 V standard has become widespread so that 230 V equipment can be used in most parts of the world with the aid of an adapter or a change to the equipment's plug to the standard for the specific country.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The United States and Canada use a supply voltage of 120 volts ± 6%.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Japan, Taiwan, Saudi Arabia, North America, Central America and some parts of northern South America use a voltage between 100 V and 127 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] However, most of the households in Japan equip split-phase electric power like the United States, which can supply 200 V by using reversed phase at the same time.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Brazil is unusual in having both 127 V and 220 V systems at 60 Hz and also permitting interchangeable plugs and sockets.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Saudi Arabia and Mexico have mixed voltage systems; in residential and light commercial buildings both countries use 127 volts, with 220 volts at 60 Hz in commercial and industrial applications.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The Saudi government approved plans in August 2010 to transition the country to a totally 230/400-volt 60 Hz system.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] A distinction should be made between the voltage at the point of supply (nominal voltage at the point of interconnection between the electrical utility and the user) and the voltage rating of the equipment (utilization or load voltage).
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Typically the utilization voltage is 3% to 5% lower than the nominal system voltage; for example, a nominal 208 V supply system will be connected to motors with "200 V" on their nameplates.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] This allows for the voltage drop between equipment and supply.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Voltages in this article are the nominal supply voltages and equipment used on these systems will carry slightly lower nameplate voltages.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Power distribution system voltage is nearly sinusoidal in nature.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Voltages are expressed as root mean square (RMS) voltage and not peak-to-peak.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Voltage tolerances are for steady-state operation.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Momentary heavy loads, or switching operations in the power distribution network, may cause short-term deviations out of the tolerance band and storms and other unusual conditions may cause even larger transient variations.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In general, power supplies derived from large networks with many sources are more stable than those supplied to an isolated community with perhaps only a single generator.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The choice of supply voltage is due more to historical reasons than optimization of the electric power distribution system—once a voltage is in use and equipment using this voltage is widespread, changing voltage is a drastic and expensive measure.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] A 230 V distribution system will use less conductor material than a 120 V system to deliver a given amount of power because the current, and consequently the resistive loss, is lower.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] While large heating appliances can use smaller conductors at 230 V for the same output rating, few household appliances use anything like the full capacity of the outlet to which they are connected.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Minimum wire size for hand-held or portable equipment is usually restricted by the mechanical strength of the conductors.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Many areas, such as the US, which use (nominally) 120 V, make use of three-wire, split-phase 240 V systems to supply large appliances.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In this system a 240 V supply has a centre-tapped neutral to give two 120 V supplies which can also supply 240 V to loads connected between the two line wires.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Three-phase systems can be connected to give various combinations of voltage, suitable for use by different classes of equipment.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Where both single-phase and three-phase loads are served by an electrical system, the system may be labelled with both voltages such as 120/208 or 230/400 V, to show the line-to-neutral voltage and the line-to-line voltage.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Large loads are connected for the higher voltage.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Other three-phase voltages, up to 830 volts, are occasionally used for special-purpose systems such as oil well pumps.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Large industrial motors (say, more than 250 hp or 150 kW) may operate on medium voltage.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] On 60 Hz systems a standard for medium voltage equipment is 2,400/4,160 V whereas 3,300 V is the common standard for 50 Hz systems.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Until 1987, mains voltage in large parts of Europe, including Germany, Austria and Switzerland, was 220±22 V while the UK used 240±14.4 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Standard ISO IEC 60038:1983 defined the new standard European voltage to be 230±23 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] From 1987 onwards, a step-wise shift towards 230+13.8 −23 V was implemented.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] From 2009 on, the voltage is permitted to be 230±23 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] No change in voltage was required by either the Central European or the UK system, as both 220 V and 240 V fall within the lower 230 V tolerance bands (230 V ±6%).
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Usually the voltage of 230 V ±3% is maintained.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Some areas of the UK still have 250 volts for legacy reasons, but these also fall within the 10% tolerance band of 230 volts.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In practice, this allowed countries to have supplied the same voltage (220 or 240 V), at least until existing supply transformers are replaced.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Equipment (with the exception of filament bulbs) used in these countries is designed to accept any voltage within the specified range.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In 2000, Australia converted to 230 V as the nominal standard with a tolerance of +10%/−6%, this superseding the old 240 V standard, AS 2926-1987.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The tolerance was increased in 2022 to ± 10% with the release of AS IEC 60038:2022.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The utilization voltage available at an appliance may be below this range, due to voltage drops within the customer installation.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] As in the UK, 240 V is within the allowable limits and "240 volt" is a synonym for mains in Australian and British English.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In the United States and Canada, national standards specify that the nominal voltage at the source should be 120 V and allow a range of 114 V to 126 V (RMS) (−5% to +5%).
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Historically, 110 V, 115 V and 117 V have been used at different times and places in North America.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Mains power is sometimes spoken of as 110 V; however, 120 V is the nominal voltage.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In Japan, the electrical power supply to households is at 100 and 200 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Eastern and northern parts of Honshū (including Tokyo) and Hokkaidō have a frequency of 50 Hz, whereas western Honshū (including Nagoya, Osaka, and Hiroshima), Shikoku, Kyūshū and Okinawa operate at 60 Hz.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The boundary between the two regions contains four back-to-back high-voltage direct-current (HVDC) substations which interconnect the power between the two grid systems; these are Shin Shinano, Sakuma Dam, Minami-Fukumitsu, and the Higashi-Shimizu Frequency Converter.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] To accommodate the difference, frequency-sensitive appliances marketed in Japan can often be switched between the two frequencies.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The world's first public electricity supply was a water wheel driven system constructed in the small English town of Godalming in 1881.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] It was an alternating current (AC) system using a Siemens alternator supplying power for both street lights and consumers at two voltages, 250 V for arc lamps, and 40 V for incandescent lamps.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The world's first large scale central plant—Thomas Edison's steam powered station at Holborn Viaduct in London—started operation in January 1882, providing direct current (DC) at 110 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The Holborn Viaduct station was used as a proof of concept for the construction of the much larger Pearl Street Station in New York, the world's first permanent commercial central power plant.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The Pearl Street Station also provided DC at 110 V, considered to be a "safe" voltage for consumers, beginning 4 September 1882.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] AC systems started appearing in the US in the mid-1880s, using higher distribution voltage stepped down via transformers to the same 110 V customer utilization voltage that Edison used.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In 1883, Edison patented a three–wire distribution system to allow DC generation plants to serve a wider radius of customers to save on copper costs.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] By connecting two groups of 110 V lamps in series more load could be served by the same size conductors run with 220 V between them; a neutral conductor carried any imbalance of current between the two sub-circuits.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] AC circuits adopted the same form during the war of the currents, allowing lamps to be run at around 110 V and major appliances to be connected to 220 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Nominal voltages gradually crept upward to 112 V and 115 V, or even 117 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] After World War II the standard voltage in the U.S. became 117 V, but many areas lagged behind even into the 1960s.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In 1954, the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) published C84.1 "American National Standard for Electric Power Systems and Equipment – Voltage Ratings (60 Hertz)".
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] This standard established 120 volt nominal system and two ranges for service voltage and utilization voltage variations.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Today, virtually all American homes and businesses have access to 120 and 240 V at 60 Hz.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Both voltages are available on the three wires (two "hot" legs of opposite phase and one "neutral" leg).
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In 1899, the Berliner Elektrizitäts-Werke (BEW), a Berlin electrical utility, decided to greatly increase its distribution capacity by switching to 220 V nominal distribution, taking advantage of the higher voltage capability of newly developed metal filament lamps.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The company was able to offset the cost of converting the customer's equipment by the resulting saving in distribution conductors cost.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] This became the model for electrical distribution in Germany and the rest of Europe and the 220 V system became common.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] North American practice remained with voltages near 110 V for lamps.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In the first decade after the introduction of alternating current in the US (from the early 1880s to about 1893) a variety of different frequencies were used, with each electric provider setting their own, so that no single one prevailed.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The most common frequency was 133+1⁄3 Hz.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The rotation speed of induction generators and motors, the efficiency of transformers, and flickering of carbon arc lamps all played a role in frequency setting.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Around 1893 the Westinghouse Electric Company in the United States and AEG in Germany decided to standardize their generation equipment on 60 Hz and 50 Hz respectively, eventually leading to most of the world being supplied at one of these two frequencies.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Today most 60 Hz systems deliver nominal 120/240 V, and most 50 Hz nominally 230 V.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The significant exceptions are in Brazil, which has a synchronized 60 Hz grid with both 127 V and 220 V as standard voltages in different regions, and Japan, which has two frequencies: 50 Hz for East Japan and 60 Hz for West Japan.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] To maintain the voltage at the customer's service within the acceptable range, electrical distribution utilities use regulating equipment at electrical substations or along the distribution line.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] At a substation, the step-down transformer will have an automatic on-load tap changer, allowing the ratio between transmission voltage and distribution voltage to be adjusted in steps.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] For long (several kilometres) rural distribution circuits, automatic voltage regulators may be mounted on poles of the distribution line.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] These are autotransformers, again, with on-load tap changers to adjust the ratio depending on the observed voltage changes.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] At each customer's service, the step-down transformer has up to five taps to allow some range of adjustment, usually ±5% of the nominal voltage.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Since these taps are not automatically controlled, they are used only to adjust the long-term average voltage at the service and not to regulate the voltage seen by the utility customer.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] The stability of the voltage and frequency supplied to customers varies among countries and regions.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] "Power quality" is a term describing the degree of deviation from the nominal supply voltage and frequency.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Short-term surges and drop-outs affect sensitive electronic equipment such as computers and flat-panel displays.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Longer-term power outages, brownouts and blackouts and low reliability of supply generally increase costs to customers, who may have to invest in uninterruptible power supply or stand-by generator sets to provide power when the utility supply is unavailable or unusable.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Erratic power supply may be a severe economic handicap to businesses and public services which rely on electrical machinery, illumination, climate control and computers.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Even the best quality power system may have breakdowns or require servicing.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] As such, companies, governments and other organizations sometimes have backup generators at sensitive facilities, to ensure that power will be available even in the event of a power outage or black out.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] Power quality can also be affected by distortions of the current or voltage waveform in the form of harmonics of the fundamental (supply) frequency, or non-harmonic (inter)modulation distortion such as that caused by electromagnetic interference.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In contrast, harmonic distortion is usually caused by conditions of the load or generator.
[src:batteryless-radio/ac-mains-supply] In multi-phase power, phase shift distortions caused by imbalanced loads can occur.
[src:batteryless-radio/ambient-backscatter] Initial implementations can communicate over several feet of distance, even if the transmission towers are up to 10.5 kilometres (6.5 mi) away.
[src:batteryless-radio/ambient-backscatter] Transmission rates were 1k bits per second between devices situated 0.45 metres (1 ft 6 in) apart inside and 0.75 metres (2 ft 6 in) apart outside, sufficient to handle text messages or other small data sets.
[src:batteryless-radio/ambient-backscatter] Circuit sizes can be as small as 1 sq. mm.
[src:batteryless-radio/ambient-backscatter] Later implementation uses Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, FM radio and LoRa transmissions.
[src:batteryless-radio/ambient-backscatter] There exists technology to extend backscatter communication range up-to 3.4 kilometers while consuming 70 μW power at the backscatter tag.
[src:batteryless-radio/ambient-backscatter] This approach would let mobile and other devices communicate without being turned on.
[src:batteryless-radio/ambient-backscatter] It would also allow unpowered sensors to communicate, allowing them to function in places where external power cannot be conveniently supplied.
[src:batteryless-radio/ambient-backscatter] In 2021, researchers integrated RF backscatter with Li-Fi to achieve greater range via PassiveLiFi.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In radio-frequency engineering, an **antenna** (American English) or **aerial** (British English) is a structure used to convert alternating electric currents into radio waves for transmission, and to convert radio waves back into electric currents for reception.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] It is the interface between radio waves propagating through space and electric currents moving in metal conductors, used with a transmitter or receiver.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In transmission, a radio transmitter supplies an electric current to the antenna's terminals, and the antenna radiates the energy from the current as electromagnetic waves (radio waves).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In reception, an antenna intercepts some of the power of a radio wave in order to produce an electric current at its terminals, that is applied to a receiver to be amplified.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are essential components of all radio equipment.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna is an array of conductor segments (elements), electrically connected to the receiver or transmitter.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas can be designed to transmit and receive radio waves in all horizontal directions equally (omnidirectional antennas), or preferentially in a particular direction (directional, or high-gain, or "beam" antennas).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna may include components not connected to the transmitter, parabolic reflectors, horns, or parasitic elements, which serve to direct the radio waves into a beam or other desired radiation pattern.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Strong directivity and good transmitting efficiency when transmitting are hard to achieve with antennas whose dimensions are much smaller than a half wavelength.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The first antennas were built in 1886 by German physicist Heinrich Hertz in his pioneering experiments to prove the existence of electromagnetic waves predicted by the 1867 electromagnetic theory of James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Hertz placed dipole antennas at the focal point of parabolic reflectors for both transmitting and receiving.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Starting in 1895, Guglielmo Marconi began development of antennas practical for long-distance wireless telegraphy and opened a factory in Chelmsford, England, to manufacture his invention in 1898.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] antenna receiving a radio wave: The electric field (E) of the wave excites oscillating currents (black arrows) in the receiver.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna radiating radio waves: The transmitter applies an alternating current (red arrows) to the rods, which charges them alternately positive and negative, emitting loops of electric field.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The arrows of the loops get reversed each time the current changes polarity.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The words *antenna* and *aerial* are used interchangeably.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Occasionally the equivalent term "aerial" is used to specifically mean an elevated horizontal wire antenna.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The origin of the word *antenna* relative to wireless apparatus is attributed to Italian radio pioneer Guglielmo Marconi.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In the summer of 1895, Marconi began testing his wireless system outdoors on his father's estate near Bologna and soon began to experiment with long wire "aerials" suspended from a pole.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In Italian a tent pole is known as *l'antenna centrale*, and the pole with the wire was simply called *l'antenna*.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Until then wireless radiating transmitting and receiving elements were known simply as "terminals".
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Because of his prominence, Marconi's use of the word *antenna* spread among wireless researchers and enthusiasts, and later to the general public.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are required by any radio receiver or transmitter to couple its electrical connection to the electromagnetic field.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Radio waves are electromagnetic waves that carry signals through space at the speed of light; in free space they propagate without material absorption, apart from geometric spreading loss.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas can be classified as omnidirectional, radiating energy approximately equally in all horizontal directions, or directional, where radio waves are concentrated in some direction(s).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A so-called beam antenna is *unidirectional* – designed for maximum response in the direction of the remote station they are aligned with – whereas many other antennas are intended to respond to stations in several directions, but are not truly omnidirectional.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Since antennas obey *reciprocity*, the same radiation pattern applies both to transmission as well as reception of radio waves.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A hypothetical antenna that radiates equally in all directions (vertical as well as all horizontal angles) is called an *isotropic radiator*; however, *exact* uniformity cannot be accomplished in practical antennas, and is only rarely desired (e.g. emergency antennas for spacecraft).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Rather, for most terrestrial communications, there is an advantage in *reducing* radiation toward the sky or ground in favor of horizontal direction(s).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Several dipole elements of slightly different lengths can be stacked in parallel, into an antenna array such as the Yagi–Uda in order to focus their radiation into a single horizontal direction, perpendicular to the stack, thus termed a *beam antenna*.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A half‑wave dipole antenna is a balanced element, with equal and opposite voltages and currents at its two terminals, and serves as a simple reference for analyzing many other antenna designs.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The vertical antenna is a *monopole* antenna, not balanced with respect to ground.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The ground (or any large conductive surface) plays the role of the second conductor of a monopole.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Since monopole antennas rely on a conductive surface, they may be mounted with a *ground plane* to approximate the effect of being mounted on the Earth's surface.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] More complex antennas increase the directivity of the antenna.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Additional elements in the antenna structure, which need not be directly connected to the receiver or transmitter, increase its directionality.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna "gain" describes the concentration of radiated power into a particular solid angle of space.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Unlike amplifier gain, which generally implies a net increase in signal power, antenna gain reflects a redistribution of power so that more is radiated in some directions and less in others, without increasing the total radiated power.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Unlike amplifiers, antennas are electrically "passive" devices which conserve total power, and there is no increase in total power above that delivered from the power source (the transmitter), only improved distribution of that fixed total.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A phased array consists of two or more simple antennas which are connected together through an electrical network.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This often involves a number of parallel dipole antennas with a certain spacing.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Depending on the relative phase introduced by the network, the same combination of dipole antennas can operate as a "broadside array" (directional normal to a line connecting the elements) or as an "end-fire array" (directional along the line connecting the elements).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna arrays may employ any basic (omnidirectional or weakly directional) antenna type, such as dipole, loop or slot antennas.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Log‑periodic and other frequency‑independent antennas employ self‑similar structures in order to operate effectively over a wide range of frequencies (i.e., with wide bandwidth).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The most familiar example is the log-periodic dipole array which can be seen as a number (typically 10 to 20) of connected dipole elements with progressive lengths in an endfire array making it rather directional; it finds use especially as a rooftop antenna for television reception.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, a Yagi–Uda antenna (or simply "Yagi"), with a somewhat similar appearance, has only one dipole element with an electrical connection; the other parasitic elements interact with the electromagnetic field in order to realize a highly directional antenna but with a narrow bandwidth.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Even greater directionality can be obtained using *aperture antennas* such as the parabolic reflector or horn antenna.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Since high directivity in an antenna depends on it being large compared to the wavelength, highly directional antennas (thus with high antenna gain) become more practical at higher frequencies (UHF and above).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] At low frequencies (such as AM broadcast), arrays of vertical towers are used to achieve directionality and they will occupy large areas of land.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] For reception, a long Beverage antenna can have significant directivity.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] For non directional portable use, a short vertical antenna or small loop antenna works well, with the main design challenge being that of impedance matching.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] With a vertical antenna a *loading coil* at the base of the antenna may be employed to cancel the reactive component of impedance; small loop antennas are tuned with parallel capacitors for this purpose.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna *lead-in* is the transmission line, or feed line, that connects the antenna to a transmitter or receiver.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The "antenna feed" may refer to all components connecting the antenna to the transmitter or receiver, such as an impedance matching network in addition to the transmission line.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A microwave antenna may also be fed directly from a waveguide in place of a (conductive) transmission line.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna counterpoise, or ground plane, is a structure of conductive material which improves or substitutes for the ground.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] It may be connected to or insulated from the natural ground.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In a monopole antenna, this aids in the function of the natural ground, particularly where variations (or limitations) of the characteristics of the natural ground interfere with its proper function.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Such a structure is normally connected to the return connection of an unbalanced transmission line such as the shield of a coaxial cable.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] An electromagnetic wave refractor in some aperture antennas is a component which due to its shape and position functions to selectively delay or advance portions of the electromagnetic wavefront passing through it.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The refractor alters the spatial characteristics of the wave on one side relative to the other side.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] It can, for instance, bring the wave to a focus or alter the wave front in other ways, generally in order to maximize the directivity of the antenna system.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This is the radio equivalent of an optical lens.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna coupling network is a passive network (generally a combination of inductive and capacitive circuit elements) used for impedance matching in between the antenna and the transmitter or receiver.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This may be used to minimize losses on the feed line, by reducing transmission line's standing wave ratio, and to present the transmitter or receiver with a standard resistive impedance needed for its optimum operation.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The feed point location(s) is selected, and antenna elements electrically similar to tuner components may be incorporated in the antenna structure itself, to improve the match.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] It is a fundamental property of antennas that most of the electrical characteristics of an antenna, such as those described in the next section (e.g. gain, radiation pattern, impedance, bandwidth, resonant frequency and polarization), are the same whether the antenna is transmitting or receiving.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This equivalence follows reciprocity theorem of electromagnetics.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Therefore, in discussions of antenna properties no distinction is usually made between receiving and transmitting terminology, and the antenna can be viewed as either transmitting or receiving, whichever is more convenient.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A necessary condition for the aforementioned reciprocity property is that the materials in the antenna and transmission medium are linear and reciprocal.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] *Reciprocal* (or *bilateral*) means that the material has the same response to an electric current or magnetic field in one direction, as it has to the field or current in the opposite direction.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Most materials used in antennas meet these conditions, but some microwave antennas use high-tech components such as isolators and circulators, made of nonreciprocal materials such as ferrite.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] These can be used to give the antenna a different behavior on receiving than it has on transmitting, which can be useful in applications like radar.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The majority of antenna designs are based on the *resonance* principle.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This relies on the behaviour of moving electrons, which reflect off surfaces where the dielectric constant changes, in a fashion similar to the way light reflects when optical properties change.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In these designs, the reflective surface is created by the end of a conductor, normally a thin metal wire or rod, which in the simplest case has a *feed point* at one end where it is connected to a transmission line.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The conductor, or *element*, is aligned with the electrical field of the desired signal, normally meaning it is perpendicular to the line from the antenna to the source (or receiver in the case of a broadcast antenna).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The radio signal's electric component induces a voltage in the conductor.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This causes an electrical current to begin flowing in the direction of the signal's instantaneous field.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] When the resulting current reaches the end of the conductor, it reflects, which is equivalent to a 180 degree change in phase.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] If the conductor is ⁠ 1 /4⁠ of a wavelength long, current from the feed point will undergo 90 degree phase change by the time it reaches the end of the conductor, reflect through 180 degrees, and then another 90 degrees as it travels back.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] That means it has undergone a total 360 degree phase change, returning it to the original signal.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The current in the element thus adds to the current being created from the source at that instant.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This process creates a standing wave in the conductor, with the maximum current at the feed.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The ordinary half-wave dipole is probably the most widely used antenna design.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This consists of two ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength elements arranged end-to-end, and lying along essentially the same axis (or *collinear*), each feeding one side of a two-conductor transmission wire.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The physical arrangement of the two elements places them 180 degrees out of phase, which means that at any given instant one of the elements is driving current into the transmission line while the other is pulling it out.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The monopole antenna is essentially one half of the half-wave dipole, a single ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength element with the other side connected to ground or an equivalent ground plane (or *counterpoise*).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Monopoles, which are one-half the size of a dipole, are common for long-wavelength radio signals where a dipole would be impractically large.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Another common design is the folded dipole which consists of two (or more) half-wave dipoles placed side by side and connected at their ends but only one of which is driven.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The standing wave forms with this desired pattern at the design operating frequency, fo, and antennas are normally designed to be this size.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] However, feeding that element with 3 fo (whose wavelength is ⁠ 1 /3⁠ that of fo) will also lead to a standing wave pattern.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Thus, an antenna element is *also* resonant when its length is ⁠ 3 /4⁠ of a wavelength.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This is true for all odd multiples of ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This allows some flexibility of design in terms of antenna lengths and feed points.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas used in such a fashion are known to be *harmonically operated*.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Resonant antennas usually use a linear conductor (or *element*), or pair of such elements, each of which is about a quarter of the wavelength in length (an odd multiple of quarter wavelengths will also be resonant).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas that are required to be small compared to the wavelength sacrifice efficiency and cannot be very directional.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Since wavelengths are so small at higher frequencies (UHF, microwaves) trading off performance to obtain a smaller physical size is usually not required.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The quarter-wave elements imitate a series-resonant electrical element due to the standing wave present along the conductor.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] At the resonant frequency, the standing wave has a current peak and voltage node (minimum) at the feed.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In electrical terms, this means that at that position, the element has minimum impedance magnitude, generating the maximum current for minimum voltage.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This is the ideal situation, because it produces the maximum output for the minimum input, producing the highest possible efficiency.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Contrary to an ideal (lossless) series-resonant circuit, a finite resistance remains (corresponding to the relatively small voltage at the feed-point) due to the antenna's resistance to radiating, as well as any conventional electrical losses from producing heat.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Recall that a current will reflect when there are changes in the electrical properties of the material.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This leads to the concept of impedance matching, the design of the overall system of antenna and transmission line so the impedance is as close as possible, thereby reducing these losses.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Impedance matching is accomplished by a circuit called an antenna tuner or impedance matching network between the transmitter and antenna.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The impedance match between the feedline and antenna is measured by a parameter called the standing wave ratio (SWR) on the feedline.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Consider a half-wave dipole designed to work with signals with wavelength 1 m, meaning the antenna would be approximately 50 cm from tip to tip.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] If the element has a length-to-diameter ratio of 1000, it will have an inherent impedance of about 63 ohms resistive.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Using the appropriate transmission wire or balun, we match that resistance to ensure minimum signal reflection.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Feeding that antenna with a current of 1 Ampere will require 63 Volts, and the antenna will radiate 63 Watts (ignoring losses) of radio frequency power.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Now consider the case when the antenna is fed a signal with a wavelength of 1.25 m; in this case the current induced by the signal would arrive at the antenna's feedpoint out-of-phase with the signal, causing the net current to drop while the voltage remains the same.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Electrically this appears to be a very high impedance.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna and transmission line no longer have the same impedance, and the signal will be reflected back into the antenna, reducing output.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This could be addressed by changing the matching system between the antenna and transmission line, but that solution only works well at the new design frequency.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The result is that the resonant antenna will efficiently feed a signal into the transmission line only when the source signal's frequency is close to that of the design frequency of the antenna, or one of the resonant multiples.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This makes resonant antenna designs inherently narrow-band: Only useful for a small range of frequencies centered around the resonance(s).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] It is possible to use simple impedance matching techniques to allow the use of monopole or dipole antennas substantially shorter than the ⁠ 1 /4⁠ or ⁠ 1 /2⁠ wave, respectively, at which they are resonant.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Sometimes the resulting (lower) electrical resonant frequency of such a system (antenna plus matching network) is described using the concept of *electrical length*.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna operated at a lower frequency than its self‑resonant frequency is then called an *electrically short antenna*.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] For example, at 30 MHz (10 m wavelength) a true resonant ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wave monopole would be almost 2.5 meters long, and using an antenna only 1.5 meters tall would require the addition of a loading coil.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Then it may be said that the coil has lengthened the antenna to achieve an electrical length of 2.5 meters.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] However, the resulting resistive impedance achieved will be quite a bit lower than that of a true ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wave (resonant) monopole, often requiring further impedance matching (a transformer) to the desired transmission line.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] For ever shorter antennas (requiring greater "electrical lengthening") the radiation resistance plummets (approximately according to the square of the antenna length), so that the mismatch due to a net reactance away from the electrical resonance worsens.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Or one could as well say that the equivalent resonant circuit of the antenna system has a higher Q factor and thus a reduced bandwidth, which can even become inadequate for the transmitted signal's spectrum.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Resistive losses due to the loading coil, relative to the decreased radiation resistance, entail a reduced electrical efficiency, which can be of great concern for a transmitting antenna, but bandwidth is the major factor that sets the size of antennas at 1 MHz and lower frequencies.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The power flux density of the field from a transmitting antenna decreases with distance according to the inverse-square law, reflecting the geometrical spreading of the wave.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] For a given incoming flux, the power captured by a receiving antenna is proportional to its *effective area*.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A half‑wave dipole, for example, has an effective area of about 0.13 λ2 when viewed from broadside.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] For an already efficient antenna design, the effective area (and thus gain) in a given direction can be increased only by reducing the gain in other directions.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] If a half-wave dipole is not connected to an external circuit but rather shorted out at the feedpoint, then it becomes a resonant half-wave element which efficiently produces a standing wave in response to an impinging radio wave.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Because there is no load to absorb that power, it retransmits all of that power, possibly with a phase shift which is critically dependent on the element's exact length.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Thus such a conductor can be arranged in order to transmit a second copy of a transmitter's signal in order to affect the radiation pattern (and feedpoint impedance) of the element electrically connected to the transmitter.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna elements used in this way are known as passive radiators.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A Yagi–Uda array uses passive elements to greatly increase gain in one direction (at the expense of other directions).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A number of parallel approximately half-wave elements (of very specific lengths) are situated parallel to each other, at specific positions, along a boom; the boom is only for support and not involved electrically.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Only one of the elements is electrically connected to the transmitter or receiver, while the remaining elements are passive.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The Yagi produces a fairly large gain (depending on the number of passive elements) and is widely used as a directional antenna with an antenna rotor to control the direction of its beam.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] It suffers from having a rather limited bandwidth, restricting its use to certain applications.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] What's more, a phased array can be made "steerable", that is, by changing the phases applied to each element the radiation pattern can be shifted *without* physically moving the antenna elements.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] When a radio wave hits a large conducting sheet it is reflected (with the phase of the electric field reversed) just as a mirror reflects light.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Placing such a reflector behind an otherwise non-directional antenna will insure that the power that would have gone in its direction is redirected toward the desired direction, increasing the antenna's gain by a factor of at least 2.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Likewise, a corner reflector can insure that all of the antenna's power is concentrated in only one quadrant of space (or less) with a consequent increase in gain.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Practically speaking, the reflector need not be a solid metal sheet, but can consist of a curtain of rods aligned with the antenna's polarization; this greatly reduces the reflector's weight and wind load.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Specular reflection of radio waves is also employed in a parabolic reflector antenna, in which a *curved* reflecting surface effects focussing of an incoming wave toward a so-called feed antenna; this results in an antenna system with an effective area comparable to the size of the reflector itself.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Other concepts from geometrical optics are also employed in antenna technology, such as with the lens antenna.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna's power gain (or simply "gain") also takes into account the antenna's efficiency, and is often the primary figure of merit.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are characterized by a number of performance measures which a user would be concerned with in selecting or designing an antenna for a particular application.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A plot of the directional characteristics in the space surrounding the antenna is its *radiation pattern*.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The frequency range or *bandwidth* over which an antenna functions well can be very wide (as in a log-periodic antenna) or narrow (as in a small loop antenna); outside this range the antenna impedance becomes a poor match to the transmission line and transmitter (or receiver).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Use of the antenna well away from its design frequency affects its radiation pattern, reducing its directive gain.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Generally an antenna will not have a feed-point impedance that matches that of a transmission line; a matching network between antenna terminals and the transmission line will improve power transfer to the antenna.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A non-adjustable matching network will most likely place further limits the usable bandwidth of the antenna system.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] It may be desirable to use tubular elements, instead of thin wires, to make an antenna; these will allow a greater bandwidth.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Or, several thin wires can be grouped in a *cage* to simulate a thicker element.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This widens the bandwidth of the resonance.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Amateur radio antennas that operate at several frequency bands which are widely separated from each other may connect elements resonant at those different frequencies in parallel.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Most of the transmitter's power will flow into the resonant element while the others present a high impedance.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Another solution uses *traps*, parallel resonant circuits which are strategically placed in breaks created in long antenna elements.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] When used at the trap's particular resonant frequency the trap presents a very high impedance (parallel resonance) effectively truncating the element at the location of the trap; if positioned correctly, the truncated element makes a proper resonant antenna at the trap frequency.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] At substantially higher or lower frequencies the trap allows the full length of the broken element to be employed, but with a resonant frequency shifted by the net reactance added by the trap.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The bandwidth characteristics of a resonant antenna element can be characterized according to its *Q* where the resistance involved is the radiation resistance, which represents the emission of energy from the resonant antenna to free space.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The *Q* of a narrow band antenna can be as high as 15.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, the reactance at the same off-resonant frequency of one using thick elements is much less, consequently resulting in a *Q* as low as 5.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] These two antennas may perform equivalently at the resonant frequency, but the second antenna will perform over a bandwidth 3 times as wide as the antenna consisting of a thin conductor.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas for use over much broader frequency ranges are achieved using further techniques.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Adjustment of a matching network can, in principle, allow for any antenna to be matched at any frequency.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Thus the small loop antenna built into most AM broadcast (medium wave) receivers has a very narrow bandwidth, but is tuned using a parallel capacitance which is adjusted according to the receiver tuning.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, log-periodic antennas are *not* resonant at any single frequency but can (in principle) be built to attain similar characteristics (including feedpoint impedance) over any frequency range.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] These are therefore commonly used (in the form of directional log-periodic dipole arrays) as television antennas.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Gain is a parameter which measures the degree of directivity of the antenna's radiation pattern.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A high-gain antenna will radiate most of its power in a particular direction, while a low-gain antenna will radiate over a wide angle.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] High-gain antennas have the advantage of longer range and better signal quality, but must be aimed carefully at the other antenna.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] An example of a high-gain antenna is a parabolic dish such as a satellite television antenna.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Low-gain antennas have shorter range, but the orientation of the antenna is relatively unimportant.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] An example of a low-gain antenna is the whip antenna found on portable radios and cordless phones.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna gain should not be confused with amplifier gain, a separate parameter measuring the increase in signal power due to an amplifying device placed at the front-end of the system, such as a low-noise amplifier.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The *effective area* or effective aperture of a receiving antenna expresses the portion of the power of a passing electromagnetic wave which the antenna delivers to its terminals, expressed in terms of an equivalent area.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] For instance, if a radio wave passing a given location has a flux of 1 pW / m2 (10−12 Watts per square meter) and an antenna has an effective area of 12 m2, then the antenna would deliver 12 pW of RF power to the receiver (30 microvolts RMS at 75 ohms).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Since the receiving antenna is not equally sensitive to signals received from all directions, the effective area is a function of the direction to the source.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Due to reciprocity (discussed above) the gain of an antenna used for transmitting must be proportional to its effective area when used for receiving.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Consider an antenna with no loss, that is, one whose electrical efficiency is 100%.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] It can be shown that its effective area averaged over all directions must be equal to λ2/4π, the wavelength squared divided by 4π.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Gain is defined such that the average gain over all directions for an antenna with 100% electrical efficiency is equal to 1.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] For an antenna with an efficiency of less than 100%, both the effective area and gain are reduced by that same amount.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Therefore, the above relationship between gain and effective area still holds.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] These are thus two different ways of expressing the same quantity.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] *A*eff is especially convenient when computing the power that would be received by an antenna of a specified gain, as illustrated by the above example.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation pattern of an antenna is a plot of the relative field strength of the radio waves emitted by the antenna at different angles in the far field.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] It is typically represented by a three-dimensional graph, or polar plots of the horizontal and vertical cross sections.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The pattern of an ideal isotropic antenna, which radiates equally in all directions, would look like a sphere.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Many nondirectional antennas, such as monopoles and dipoles, emit equal power in all horizontal directions, with the power dropping off at higher and lower angles; this is called an omnidirectional pattern and when plotted looks like a torus or donut.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation of many antennas shows a pattern of maxima or "*lobes*" at various angles, separated by "*nulls*", angles where the radiation falls to zero.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] This is because the radio waves emitted by different parts of the antenna typically interfere, causing maxima at angles where the radio waves arrive at distant points in phase, and zero radiation at other angles where the radio waves arrive out of phase.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In a directional antenna designed to project radio waves in a particular direction, the lobe in that direction is designed larger than the others and is called the "*main lobe*".
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The other lobes usually represent unwanted radiation and are called "*sidelobes*".
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The axis through the main lobe is called the "*principal axis*" or "*boresight axis*".
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The polar radiation patterns of Yagi antennas become narrower, and their directivity (and thus gain) increases, when they are designed for a relatively narrow frequency range, as compared with wideband designs.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The space surrounding an antenna can be divided into three concentric regions: The reactive near-field (also called the inductive near-field), the radiating near-field (Fresnel region) and the far-field (Fraunhofer) regions.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] These regions are useful to identify the field structure in each, although the transitions between them are gradual; there are no clear boundaries.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The orientation and physical structure of an antenna determine the *polarization* of the electric field of the radio wave transmitted by it.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] For instance, an antenna composed of a linear conductor (such as a dipole or whip antenna) oriented vertically will result in vertical polarization; if turned on its side the same antenna's polarization will be horizontal.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In the most general case, polarization is elliptical, meaning that over each cycle the electric field vector traces out an ellipse.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Two special cases are linear polarization (the ellipse collapses into a line) as discussed above, and circular polarization (in which the two axes of the ellipse are equal).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In linear polarization the electric field of the radio wave oscillates along one direction.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In circular polarization, the electric field of the radio wave rotates around the axis of propagation.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Circular or elliptically polarized radio waves are designated as right-handed or left-handed using the "thumb in the direction of the propagation" rule.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Note that for circular polarization, optical researchers use the opposite right-hand rule from the one used by radio engineers.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] It is best for the receiving antenna to match the polarization of the transmitted wave for optimum reception.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Otherwise there will be a loss of signal strength: when a linearly polarized antenna receives linearly polarized radiation at a relative angle of θ, then there will be a power loss of cos2θ .
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] A circularly polarized antenna can be used to equally well match vertical or horizontal linear polarizations, suffering a 3 dB signal reduction.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] However it will be blind to a circularly polarized signal of the opposite orientation.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Maximum power transfer requires matching the impedance of an antenna system (as seen looking into the transmission line) to the complex conjugate of the impedance of the receiver or transmitter.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The intended impedance is normally resistive, but a transmitter (and some receivers) may have limited additional adjustments to cancel a certain amount of reactance, in order to "tweak" the match.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The match is sought to minimize the amplitude of standing waves (measured via the standing wave ratio; SWR) that a mismatch raises on the line, and the increase in transmission line losses it entails.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna tuning, in the strict sense of modifying the antenna itself, generally refers only to cancellation of any reactance seen at the antenna terminals, leaving only a resistive impedance which might or might not be exactly the desired impedance (that of the available transmission line).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Although an antenna may be designed to have a purely resistive feedpoint impedance (such as a dipole 97% of a half wavelength long) at just one frequency, this will very likely not be exactly true at other frequencies that the antenna is eventually used for.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In most cases, in principle the physical length of the antenna can be "trimmed" to obtain a pure resistance, although this is rarely convenient.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, the addition of a contrary inductance or capacitance can be used to cancel a residual capacitive or inductive reactance, respectively, and may be more convenient than lowering and trimming or extending the antenna, then hoisting it back.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In addition to those reactance-neutralizing add-ons, antennas of any kind may include a transformer and / or transformer balun at their feedpoint, to change the resistive part of the impedance to more nearly match the feedline's characteristic impedance.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] An additional problem is matching the remaining resistive impedance to the characteristic impedance of the transmission line: A general impedance matching network (an "antenna tuner" or ATU) will have at least two adjustable elements to correct both components of impedance.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Any matching network will have both power losses and power restrictions when used for transmitting.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Commercial antennas are generally designed to approximately match standard 50 Ohm coaxial cables, at standard frequencies; the design expectation is that a matching network will be merely used to 'tweak' any residual mismatch.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] In some cases matching is done in a more extreme manner, not simply to cancel a small amount of residual reactance, but to resonate an antenna whose resonance frequency is quite different from the intended frequency of operation.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The physically large inductor at the base of the antenna has an inductive reactance which is the opposite of the capacitative reactance that the short vertical antenna has at the desired operating frequency.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] (usually, but not always, for receiving) at a relatively low frequency, where it appears almost as a pure inductor.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] to produce a better-matched feedpoint resistance.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The loop is resonated by a coupled tuning capacitor, which is configured to match the receiver's tuning, in order to keep the antenna resonant at the chosen receive frequency over the AM broadcast band.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Ground reflections is one of the common types of multipath.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation pattern and even the driving point impedance of an antenna can be influenced by the dielectric constant and especially conductivity of nearby objects.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] For a terrestrial antenna, the ground is usually one such object of importance.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna's height above the ground, as well as the electrical properties (permittivity and conductivity) of the ground, can then be important.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Also, in the particular case of a monopole antenna, the ground (or an artificial ground plane) serves as the return connection for the antenna current thus having an additional effect, particularly on the impedance seen by the feed line.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] When an electromagnetic wave strikes a plane surface such as the ground, part of the wave is transmitted into the ground and part of it is reflected, according to the Fresnel coefficients.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] If the ground is a very good conductor then almost all of the wave is reflected (180° out of phase), whereas a ground modeled as a (lossy) dielectric can absorb a large amount of the wave's power.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The power remaining in the reflected wave, and the phase shift upon reflection, strongly depend on the wave's angle of incidence and polarization.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The dielectric constant and conductivity (or simply the complex dielectric constant) is dependent on the soil type and is a function of frequency.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] At lower mediumwave frequencies the ground acts mainly as a good conductor, which AM broadcast (0.5–1.7 MHz) antennas depend on.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] At frequencies between 3–30 MHz, a large portion of the energy from a horizontally polarized antenna reflects off the ground, with almost total reflection at the grazing angles important for ground wave propagation.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] That reflected wave, with its phase reversed, can either cancel or reinforce the direct wave, depending on the antenna height in wavelengths and elevation angle (for a sky wave).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, vertically polarized radiation is not well reflected by the ground except at grazing incidence or over very highly conducting surfaces such as sea water.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] However the grazing angle reflection important for ground wave propagation, using vertical polarization, is *in phase* with the direct wave, providing a boost of up to 6 dB, as is detailed below.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] At VHF and above (> 30 MHz) the ground becomes a poorer reflector.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] However, for shortwave frequencies, especially below ~15 MHz, it remains a good reflector especially for horizontal polarization and grazing angles of incidence.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] That is important as these higher frequencies usually depend on horizontal line-of-sight propagation (except for satellite communications), the ground then behaving almost as a mirror.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] The net quality of a ground reflection depends on the topography of the surface.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] When the irregularities of the surface are much smaller than the wavelength, the dominant regime is that of specular reflection, and the receiver sees both the real antenna and an image of the antenna under the ground due to reflection.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] But if the ground has irregularities not small compared to the wavelength, reflections will not be coherent but shifted by random phases.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] With shorter wavelengths (higher frequencies), this is generally the case.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] Whenever both the receiving or transmitting antenna are placed at significant heights above the ground (relative to the wavelength), waves reflected specularly by the ground will travel a longer distance than direct waves, inducing a phase shift which can sometimes be significant.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p01] When a sky wave is launched by such an antenna, that phase shift is always significant unless the antenna is very close to the ground (compared to the wavelength).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] The flow of current in wire antennas is identical to the solution of counter-propagating waves in a single conductor transmission line, which can be solved using the telegrapher's equations.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Unlike transmission lines, currents in antennas contribute power to the radiated part electromagnetic field, which can be modeled using radiation resistance.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] The combination of the incident and reflected wave, just as in a transmission line, forms a standing wave with a current node at the conductor's end, and a voltage node one-quarter wavelength from the end (if the element is at least that long).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] In a *resonant antenna*, the feedpoint of the antenna is at one of those voltage nodes.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Due to discrepancies from the simplified version of the transmission line model, the voltage one quarter wavelength from the current node is not exactly zero, but it is near a minimum, and small compared to the much larger voltage at the conductor's end.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Hence, a feed point matching the antenna at that spot requires a relatively small voltage but large current (the currents from the two waves add in-phase there), thus a relatively low feedpoint impedance.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Feeding the antenna at other points involves a large voltage, thus a large impedance, and usually one that is primarily reactive (low power factor), which is a terrible impedance match to available transmission lines.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Therefore, it is usually desired for an antenna to operate as a resonant element with each conductor having a length of one quarter wavelength (or any other odd multiples of a quarter wavelength).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] For instance, a half-wave dipole has two such elements (one connected to each conductor of a balanced transmission line) about one quarter wavelength long.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Depending on the conductors' diameters, a small deviation from this length is adopted in order to reach the point where the antenna current and the (small) feedpoint voltage are exactly in phase.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Then the antenna presents a purely resistive impedance, and ideally one close to the characteristic impedance of an available transmission line.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Despite these useful properties, resonant antennas have the disadvantage that they achieve resonance (purely resistive feedpoint impedance) only at a fundamental frequency, and perhaps some of its harmonics, and the feedpoint resistance is larger at higher-order resonances.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Therefore, resonant antennas can only achieve their good performance within a limited bandwidth, depending on the Q at the resonance.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] The electric and magnetic fields emanating from a driven antenna element will generally affect the voltages and currents in nearby antennas, antenna elements, or other conductors.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] This is particularly true when the affected conductor is a resonant element (multiple of half-wavelengths in length) at about the same frequency, as is the case where the conductors are all part of the same active or passive antenna array.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Thus using the mutual impedances calculated for a specific geometry, one can solve for the radiation pattern of a Yagi–Uda antenna or the currents and voltages for each element of a phased array.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Such an analysis can also describe in detail reflection of radio waves by a ground plane or by a corner reflector and their effect on the impedance (and radiation pattern) of an antenna in its vicinity.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Often such near-field interactions are undesired and pernicious.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Currents in random metal objects near a transmitting antenna will often be in poor conductors, causing loss of RF power in addition to unpredictably altering the characteristics of the antenna.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] By careful design, it is possible to reduce the electrical interaction between nearby conductors.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] For instance, the 90 degree angle in between the two dipoles composing the turnstile antenna ensures no interaction between these, allowing these to be driven independently (but actually with the same signal in quadrature phases in the turnstile antenna design).
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Antennas can be classified by operating principles or by their application.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] Different authorities placed antennas in narrower or broader categories.
[src:batteryless-radio/antenna-radio-p02] These antenna types and others are summarized in greater detail in the overview article, Antenna types, as well as in each of the linked articles in the list above, and in even more detail in articles which those link to.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] An **antique radio** is a radio receiving set that is collectible because of its age and rarity.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The first radio receivers used a coherer and sounding board, and were only able to receive continuous wave (CW) transmissions, encoded with Morse code (wireless telegraphy).
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Later transmission and reception of speech became possible, although Morse code transmission continued in use until the 1990s.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] All the following sections concern speech-capable radio, or wireless telephony.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The idea of radio as entertainment took off in 1920, with the opening of the first stations established specifically for broadcast to the public such as KDKA in Pittsburgh and WWJ in Detroit.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] More stations opened in cities across North America in the following years and radio ownership steadily gained in popularity.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Radio sets from before 1920 are rarities, and are probably military artifacts.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Sets made prior to approximately 1924 were usually made on wooden breadboards, in small cupboard style cabinets, or sometimes on an open sheet metal chassis.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Homemade sets remained a strong sector of radio production until the early 1930s.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Until then there were more homemade sets in use than commercial sets.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] These basic radios used no battery, had no amplification and could operate only high-impedance headphones.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] They would receive only very strong signals from a local station.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] They were popular among the less wealthy due to their low build cost and zero run cost.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Crystal sets had minimal ability to separate stations, and where more than one high power station was present, inability to receive one without the other was a common problem.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Some crystal set users added a carbon amplifier or a mechanical turntable amplifier to give enough output to operate a speaker.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Tuned radio frequency sets (TRF sets) were the most popular class of early radio, primarily because the Radio Corporation of America (RCA) had a monopoly on the superheterodyne circuit patents and it was more profitable for companies to jump into radio manufacturing TRF sets.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] These used several valves (tubes) to provide RF amplification, detection, and audio amplification.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Early TRF sets only operated headphones, but by the mid-1920s it was more common to use additional amplification to power a loudspeaker, despite the expense.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The sound quality produced from "moving-iron" speakers used on such sets is sometimes described as torturous, although by the late 1920s the Kellogg-Rice dynamic (moving-coil) speaker had begun to find favor due to its superior sound-reproduction ability.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] TRF sets used no regeneration, and were merely several stages (typically three) of tuned RF amplifiers in series feeding a detector tube which extracted the audio intelligence from the RF signal.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] TRF sets, depending on the number of stages they employed, could have poor-to-superb sensitivity (ability of the set to pick up faint signals) and corresponding selectivity (ability to parse adjacent stations from one another).
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Audio reproduction quality of TRF sets was limited by the available loudspeakers.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] "High Fidelity" was not to become a radio marketing concept until the mid-1930s and was not realized until the advent of FM broadcasting.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Reaction sets, also known as regenerative receivers, rely on positive feedback to achieve adequate gain.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] This approach provided high performance with a minimum number of expensive vacuum tubes, but these receivers tended to radiate RF interference in their immediate vicinity.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Consequently, there was a significant amount of hostility by neighbors of "regen" set users over maladjusted radios transmitting squealing noises and blocking reception on nearby properties.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Early TRF sets had typically two or three tuning knobs and tube filament voltage-control rheostats, all of which had to be set correctly to receive a station.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Later (late 1920s) TRF sets had ganged tuning (one knob was used to control all stage tuning capacitors simultaneously), AC house current operation, and eliminated the filament voltage adjustments.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] All of these changes greatly simplified operation and made radio a household appliance that even a small child could operate, instead of the highly skilled hobbyists of the brief preceding generation.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Reaction sets also had the filament adjustment rheostats for each valve, and again settings had to be right to achieve reception.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] In the era of early radio, only RCA and a select number of competing "prestige" radio manufacturers could afford to build a superheterodyne receiver (superhet).
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] RCA had exclusive rights to the superheterodyne circuit patents and extracted high licensing fees from other companies who sought to build superhet sets.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] RCA also vigorously prosecuted patent infringers.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] This situation helped propel RCA to the forefront of radio manufacturers in the 1920s due to the higher efficiency of the superhet circuit—a situation which lasted until the patents expired in the early 1930s, at which time a flood of low-cost superheterodyne receivers hit the market.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Early (RCA-patent-era) superhets were often used with the relatively expensive moving coil speakers, which offer a quality of sound unavailable from moving iron speakers.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Most post-1932 commercial radios were superhets, and this technology is still in widespread use in radio receivers today, implemented with transistors or integrated circuits.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] In general the technical and manufacturing advantages of the superhet ensured that the TRF set became quickly obsolete once the patent restrictions on superhets were eliminated.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Prior to the Rural Electrification Act of 1936, the vast majority of rural farms in America did not have electricity.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Many rural areas of the Midwest and South did not receive commercial power until the 1960s.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Until that point, special radios were made to run on DC power.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The earliest so-called "farm radios" used the "A", "B", and "C" batteries typical of 1920s radio sets; these farm radios were identical to those used in cities.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Other farm radios were designed to run on 32 V DC, from a bank of lead-acid storage batteries charged from a gas powered generator or a wind-charger.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The 32-volt system could also power other specially made appliances as well as electric lights around the farm.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Other farm radios, especially from the late 1930s to the 1950s, reverted to using a large "A-B" dry cell that provided both 90 V for the tube plates and 1.5 V for the tube filaments, as did most tube-based portable radios of that era.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] World War 2 created widespread urgent need for radio communication, and foxhole sets were built by people without access to traditional radio parts.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] A foxhole radio is a simple crystal set radio receiver cobbled together from whatever parts one could make (which were very few indeed) or scrounged from junked equipment.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Such a set typically used salvaged domestic wiring for an antenna, a double-edged safety-razor blade and pencil lead (or bent safety-pin) for a detector, and a tin can, magnet and some wire for an earpiece.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Razor blades of the era were chemically coated ("blued") and this coating could function as a diode, in the same way that a galena cat's whisker detector operates.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The console radio was the center piece of household entertainment in the era of radio.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] They were big and expensive, beautifully made wood cabinets, often costing hundreds of dollars in the late Depression era 1930s and were often coupled with a phonograph.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] These tended to be a major acquisition for a middle-class family, and these large console radios were usually placed in the living room.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Most very early console radios were tall and narrow, but as the years went on they got shorter and wider in accordance with the Art Deco design precepts which had become popular.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Consumer console radios were made by RCA, Philco, General Electric, Montgomery Ward (under the Airline brand name), Sears (under the Silvertone brand name), Westinghouse, Zenith and others.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Brands such as Zenith and Stromberg-Carlson made a few high-end high-priced models ("Stratosphere"), but mainly they produced moderately priced radios.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Motorola had radios in many cars by 1940 using the previously mentioned vibrator power supply necessary for tube operation.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Scott and Silver-Marshall started around $500–$800 range in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The availability of the first mass-produced plastic Bakelite allowed designers much more creativity in cabinet styling, and significantly reduced costs.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] However, Bakelite is a very brittle plastic, and dropping a radio could easily crack or break the case.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Bakelite is a brown-black mouldable thermosetting plastic, and is still used in some products today.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] In the 1930s some radios were manufactured using Catalin, which is the phenolic resin component of bakelite, with no organic filler added, but nearly all historic bakelite radios are the standard black-brown bakelite color.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Bakelite as used for radio cabinets was traditionally brown, and this color came from the ground walnut-shell flour added to the thermosetting phenolic resin as an extender and strengthening agent.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The affordability of more modern light coloured thermoplastics in the 1950s made brighter designs practical.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Some of these thermoplastics are slightly translucent.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The invention of the transistor made it possible to produce very small portable radios that did not need a warm-up time, and ran on much smaller batteries.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] They were convenient, though the prices were initially high and the sound quality of early models was not nearly as good as tube radios.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Later models equalled or surpassed tube models in audio quality.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Transistors also made it possible to manufacture portable FM radios, which was impractical using tubes.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Transistor radios were available in many sizes from console to table-top to matchbox.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Transistors are still used in today's radios, though the integrated circuit containing a large number of transistors has surpassed the use of singly packed transistors for the majority of radio circuitry.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Transistor radios appeared on the market in 1954, but at a high price.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] By the 1960s, reduced prices and an increase in desire for portability made them very popular.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] There was something of a marketing war over the number of transistors sets contained, with many models named after this number.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Some sets even had non-functional reject transistors soldered to the circuit board, doing absolutely nothing, so the sales pitch could advertise a higher number of transistors.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Vacuum tube radios and early transistor radios were hand assembled.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Today radios are designed with the assistance of computers and manufactured with much greater use of machinery.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Today's radios are usually uneconomical to repair because mass production and technological improvements in numerous areas have made them so inexpensive to buy, while the cost of human labor and workshop overheads have increased greatly in comparison.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The earliest car radios appeared not long after commercial radio broadcasts commenced, but were experimental only.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] They were expensive, required a large aerial, reception was inconsistent, and they required adjustment in use, which was not very practical.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] By the early 1930s most car radios, no longer experimental, were superheterodynes and used a vibrator power supply to step up the low voltage to high voltage ("B+" voltage of anywhere from 90 to 250 V) for the vacuum tubes.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Vibrators are relatively unreliable as electromechanical components of limited life, buzz audibly, and produce radio interference.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] A few radios used a bulkier and more expensive motor-generator or motor-alternator set called a "dynamotor" that spun a high-voltage generator or alternator using a 6- or 12-volt DC motor.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Filaments were powered using 6- and later 12-volt DC power from the vehicle's electrical system directly.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] With the introduction of transistors, the earlier ones suitable for audio frequencies only, car radios were valve sets with a transistor output stage; makers promoted them as transistor sets.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Some historic car radios badged as transistorised are in reality of this type.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] All-transistor sets eventually replaced sets with vacuum tube after transistor technology improved and prices fell significantly.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Chrysler and Philco announced an all-transistor car radio in the April 28, 1955, edition of the Wall Street Journal.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] This Philco car radio model was the first tubeless auto set in history to be developed and produced.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] It was a $150 option for 1956 Chrysler and Imperial cars and hit the showroom floor on October 21, 1955.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Most valve sets needed a few seconds for the valves to heat up, though there were exceptions.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Warm-up times changed as valves went through several generations of design.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Using vintage radios generally requires inspection and repair or refurbishment before they can be safely operated.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] In their original state, they complied only with the limited safety standards of the time, and almost none used fuses.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] AC-operated radios using power transformers require repair and refurbishment of the power supply section before operation, as any failures are likely to stress or damage the power transformer, necessitating a costly repair.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] AC/DC sets not using a power transformer may be either "curtain burners" using a resistance cord to drop the line voltage, or warm/hot chassis radios using a series-string filament circuit where the voltages add up to the line voltage.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] They were named "AC/DC" because they operated on either AC or DC line voltage, which was not possible with a transformer-based set.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] "Curtain Burner" sets were common in the early 1930s "midget" sets.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The name is an indication of the problem—the line cord contained resistors to drop the voltage and dissipated substantial power in the cord itself.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] When operating properly and the line cord was stretched to full length, the cord got "warm" and was safe enough (until the heat made the rubber insulation crack).
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] When the cord was coiled up or otherwise insulated (like from a curtain resting on it) it could get very hot, and frequently caused a fire.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Resistance line cords are no longer available and the vintage cords are no longer serviceable, so the radio must be partially redesigned with either a dropping capacitor, dropping resistor, or some other workaround for safe operation.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] AC/DC sets lacking resistance line cords instead used tube filaments in series that added up to the line voltage, effectively moving the resistance into the radio.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] These are the most common vintage radio in the US after about 1940 or so, as they were very inexpensive to manufacture.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] They are much less common in areas with 240 mains power, as there were few common tubes built to operate at the high voltages required.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] BC (medium wave/"AM") only radios like the "All American 5" design, and later AM/FM radios with more tubes, and even televisions were built using the same idea, because of the simplicity and low cost possible.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Either type of AC/DC radio can present the "hot" line of the line voltage on the chassis of the radio ("hot chassis") or isolated from the chassis by a single capacitor ("warm chassis").
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] This presents a safety problem, as depending on the direction of the non-polarized plug, the hot side of the line voltage can be connected directly to all the metal parts of the radio any time it is plugged in, regardless of whether it is powered on or not.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Proper repair or refurbishment requires an isolation transformer to remove the live connection, and care should be taken to never touch any metal part of the radio (chassis mounting screws, bare control shafts, etc.) when the radio is plugged in.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Many radios with a hot chassis use interlocks on the back to ensure that the line is disconnected before the rear can be accessed for tube replacement.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Later transistor-based AC table radios typically used power transformers and operate safely, but with likely hum from failed electrolytic capacitors in the power supply, and likely low volume from other failed electrolytic coupling capacitors.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] There were a few early transistor table radios using "hot chassis" principles, but these are very rare.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The minority of all-in-one commercial ac mains sets that appeared in the 1930s were entirely self-sufficient, containing built in antennas, speakers, and power supplies.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Such sets should be checked for the possible existence of live metalwork accessible to the user, and a general safety check is advisable.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] However, many radios from before the Great Depression contain only the receiver circuitry.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The rest of the unit was generally not self contained and the user would need to construct a receiving antenna and often provide dry battery power.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The sound quality of antique radios depends on the technologies used in the set.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The type of speaker is the main differentiator, with mains or battery also making a significant difference.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] All valve sets produce 2nd harmonic distortion, which is fairly euphonic.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Some also produce significant 3rd harmonic distortion, which is less pleasant to the ear.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Discussion is often heard about the distortion of triode versus pentode valves, and single ended versus push pull, which affect the types of distortion produced, but these issues seem to be secondary in practice to the ones discussed in this article, and are already well covered in other articles.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Homemade pre-war sets usually used some form of moving iron speaker, usually horn or cone loaded, and occasionally disc loaded.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The sound quality of such radios is generally unimportant, since almost any defect in the audio signal will be masked by the butchery visited upon it by the loudspeaker.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The question of sound quality is heavily dominated by the speaker in these cases.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The sound of moving iron speakers has a strong unmistakable character.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] They were far from faithful in their reproduction of audio, and their technical specifications were poorly controlled.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] An example of this is their electrical impedance, which varied across the audio spectrum by a ratio of more than 100:1.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] It is not unusual for an electronics student, on hearing some of the specs of these devices, to conclude that they could not have been capable of reproducing speech.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Yet they do, and with a sound that can not be mistaken for anything else.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] These enjoyed brief success but were quickly eclipsed by moving coil speakers.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The Inductor Dynamic Speaker solved the worst problems of earlier moving iron types, and provided a relatively pleasant listening experience.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] The main defect of ID speakers was poor treble response, giving them a characteristic dull drone.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] These speakers were mostly of sufficient quality that the radio's characteristics become significant.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] Transformer coupled sets suffered loss of bass & reduced treble, grid leak sets where rf and af were amplified by the same valve gave some nonlinearity, and output stages always provided a little more non-linearity.
[src:batteryless-radio/antique-radio] However the quality of a moving coil equipped set can be pleasant, and mistakable for a modern portable radio.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:batteryless-radio/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] An **electric battery** is a source of electric power consisting of one or more electrochemical cells with external connections for powering electrical devices.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] When a battery is supplying power, its positive terminal is the cathode and its negative terminal is the anode.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The terminal marked negative is the source of electrons.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] When a battery is connected to an external electric load, those negatively charged electrons flow through the circuit and reach the positive terminal, thus causing a redox reaction by attracting positively charged ions, or cations.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Thus, higher energy reactants are converted to lower energy products, and the free-energy difference is delivered to the external circuit as electrical energy.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Historically the term "battery" specifically referred to a device composed of multiple cells; however, the usage has evolved to include devices composed of a single cell.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Primary (single-use or "disposable") batteries are used once and discarded, as the electrode materials are irreversibly changed during discharge; a common example is the alkaline battery used for flashlights and a multitude of portable electronic devices.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Secondary (rechargeable) batteries can be discharged and recharged multiple times using an applied electric current; the original composition of the electrodes can be restored by reverse current.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Examples include the lead–acid automotive battery used in internal combustion engine vehicles, and lithium-ion batteries used for portable electronics and electric cars.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Batteries come in many shapes and sizes, from miniature cells used to power hearing aids and wristwatches to, at the largest extreme, huge battery banks the size of rooms that provide standby or emergency power for telephone exchanges and computer data centers.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Batteries have much lower specific energy (energy per unit mass) than common fuels such as gasoline.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In automobiles, this is somewhat offset by the higher efficiency of electric motors in converting electrical energy to mechanical work, compared to combustion engines.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Benjamin Franklin first used the term "battery" in 1749 when he was doing experiments with electricity using a set of linked Leyden jar capacitors.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Franklin grouped a number of the jars into what he described as a "battery", using the military term for weapons functioning together.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] By multiplying the number of holding vessels, a stronger charge could be stored, and more power would be available on discharge.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Italian physicist Alessandro Volta built and described the first electrochemical battery, the voltaic pile, in 1800.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] This was a stack of copper and zinc plates, separated by brine-soaked paper disks, that could produce a steady current for a considerable length of time.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Volta did not understand that the voltage was due to chemical reactions.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] He thought that his cells were an inexhaustible source of energy, and that the associated corrosion effects at the electrodes were a mere nuisance, rather than an unavoidable consequence of their operation, as Michael Faraday showed in 1834.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Although early batteries were of great value for experimental purposes, in practice their voltages fluctuated and they could not provide a large current for a sustained period.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The Daniell cell, invented in 1836 by British chemist John Frederic Daniell, was the first practical source of electricity, becoming an industry standard and seeing widespread adoption as a power source for electrical telegraph networks.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] It consisted of a copper pot filled with a copper sulfate solution, in which was immersed an unglazed earthenware container filled with sulfuric acid and a zinc electrode.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] These wet cells used liquid electrolytes, which were prone to leakage and spillage if not handled correctly.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Many used glass jars to hold their components, which made them fragile and potentially dangerous.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] These characteristics made wet cells unsuitable for portable appliances.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Near the end of the nineteenth century, the invention of dry cell batteries, which replaced the liquid electrolyte with a paste, made portable electrical devices practical.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Batteries in vacuum tube devices historically used a wet cell for the "A" battery (to provide power to the filament) and a dry cell for the "B" battery (to provide the plate voltage).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Between 2010 and 2018, battery demand grew by 30% annually, reaching a total of 180 GWh in 2018.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Conservatively, the growth rate is expected to be maintained at an estimated 25%, culminating in demand reaching 2600 GWh in 2030.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In addition, cost reductions are expected to further increase the demand to as much as 3562 GWh.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Important reasons for this high rate of growth of the electric battery industry include the electrification of transport, and large-scale deployment in electricity grids, supported by decarbonization initiatives.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Distributed electric batteries, such as those used in battery electric vehicles (vehicle-to-grid) and in home energy storage with smart metering and that are connected to smart grids for demand response are active participants in smart power supply grids.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Secondary use of partially depleted batteries can add to the overall utility of electric batteries by reducing energy storage costs and emission impact due to longer service life.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In this use, vehicle electric batteries that have their battery capacity reduced to less than 80% (usually after 5–8 years of service) are repurposed for use in backup supplies or renewable energy storage systems.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage envisages the large-scale use of batteries to collect and store energy from the grid or a power plant and then discharge that energy at a later time to provide electricity or other grid services when needed.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage (either turnkey or distributed) are important components of smart power supply grids.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The advent of computational modeling has revolutionized battery materials design, enabling high-throughput screening and atomistic simulations that accelerate the discovery of novel electrolytes and electrodes, moving beyond traditional trial-and-error approaches.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Batteries convert chemical energy directly to electrical energy.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In many cases, the electrical energy released is the difference in the cohesive or bond energies of the metals, oxides, or molecules undergoing the electrochemical reaction.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] For instance, energy can be stored in Zn or Li, which are high-energy metals because they are not stabilized by d-electron bonding, unlike transition metals.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Batteries are designed so that the energetically favorable redox reaction can occur only when electrons move through the external part of the circuit.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A battery consists of some number of voltaic cells.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Each cell consists of two half-cells connected in series by a conductive electrolyte containing metal *cations*.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] One half-cell includes electrolyte and the negative electrode, the electrode to which anions (negatively charged ions) migrate; the other half-cell includes electrolyte and the positive electrode, to which cations (positively charged ions) migrate.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Cations are reduced (electrons are added) at the cathode, while metal atoms are oxidized (electrons are removed) at the anode.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Some cells use different electrolytes for each half-cell; then a separator is used to prevent mixing of the electrolytes while allowing ions to flow between half-cells to complete the electrical circuit.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Each half-cell has an electromotive force (*emf*, measured in volts) relative to a standard.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The net emf of the cell is the difference between the emfs of its half-cells.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Thus, if the electrodes have emfs ${\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ and ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}$ , then the net emf is ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}-{\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ ; in other words, the net emf is the difference between the reduction potentials of the half-reactions.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The electrical driving force or $\displaystyle {\Delta V_{\text{bat}}}$ across the terminals of a cell is known as the *terminal voltage (difference)* and is measured in volts.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The terminal voltage of a cell that is neither charging nor discharging is called the open-circuit voltage and equals the emf of the cell.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Because of internal resistance, the terminal voltage of a cell that is discharging is smaller in magnitude than the open-circuit voltage and the terminal voltage of a cell that is charging exceeds the open-circuit voltage.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] An ideal cell has negligible internal resistance, so it would maintain a constant terminal voltage of ${\mathcal {E}}$ until exhausted, then dropping to zero.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] If such a cell maintained 1.5 volts and produced a charge of one coulomb then on complete discharge it would have performed 1.5 joules of work.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In actual cells, the internal resistance increases under discharge and the open-circuit voltage also decreases under discharge.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] If the voltage and resistance are plotted against time, the resulting graphs typically are a curve; the shape of the curve varies according to the chemistry and internal arrangement employed.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The voltage developed across a cell's terminals depends on the energy release of the chemical reactions of its electrodes and electrolyte.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Alkaline and zinc–carbon cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.5 volts; likewise NiCd and NiMH cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.2 volts.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The high electrochemical potential changes in the reactions of lithium compounds give lithium cells emfs of 3 volts or more.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Almost any liquid or moist object that has enough ions to be electrically conductive can serve as the electrolyte for a cell.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] As a novelty or science demonstration, it is possible to insert two electrodes made of different metals into a lemon, potato, etc. and generate small amounts of electricity.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A voltaic pile can be made from two coins (such as a nickel and a penny) and a piece of paper towel dipped in salt water.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Such a pile generates a very low voltage but, when many are stacked in series, they can replace normal batteries for a short time.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Some types of primary batteries used, for example, for telegraph circuits, were restored to operation by replacing the electrodes.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries are not indefinitely rechargeable due to dissipation of the active materials, loss of electrolyte and internal corrosion.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Primary batteries, or primary cells, can produce current immediately on assembly.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] These are most commonly used in portable devices that have low current drain, are used only intermittently, or are used well away from an alternative power source, such as in alarm and communication circuits where other electric power is only intermittently available.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Disposable primary cells cannot be reliably recharged, since the chemical reactions are not easily reversible and active materials may not return to their original forms.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Battery manufacturers recommend against attempting to recharge primary cells.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In general, these have higher energy densities than rechargeable batteries, but disposable batteries do not fare well under high-drain applications with loads under 75 ohms (75 Ω).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Common types of disposable batteries include zinc–carbon batteries and alkaline batteries.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries, also known as *secondary cells*, or *rechargeable batteries*, must be charged before first use; they are usually assembled with active materials in the discharged state.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Rechargeable batteries are (re)charged by applying electric current, which reverses the chemical reactions that occur during discharge/use.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Devices to supply the appropriate current are called chargers.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The oldest form of rechargeable battery is the lead–acid battery, which are widely used in automotive and boating applications.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] This technology contains liquid electrolyte in an unsealed container, requiring that the battery be kept upright and the area be well ventilated to ensure safe dispersal of the hydrogen gas it produces during overcharging.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The lead–acid battery is relatively heavy for the amount of electrical energy it can supply.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Its low manufacturing cost and its high surge current levels make it common where its capacity (over approximately 10 Ah) is more important than weight and handling issues.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A common application is the modern car battery, which can, in general, deliver a peak current of 450 amperes.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Many types of electrochemical cells have been produced, with varying chemical processes and designs, including galvanic cells, electrolytic cells, fuel cells, flow cells and voltaic piles.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A *wet cell* battery has a liquid electrolyte.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Other names are *flooded cell*, since the liquid covers all internal parts or *vented cell*, since gases produced during operation can escape to the air.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Wet cells were a precursor to dry cells and are commonly used as a learning tool for electrochemistry.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] They can be built with common laboratory supplies, such as beakers, for demonstrations of how electrochemical cells work.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A particular type of wet cell known as a concentration cell is important in understanding corrosion.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Wet cells may be primary cells (non-rechargeable) or secondary cells (rechargeable).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Originally, all practical primary batteries, such as the Daniell cell, were built as open-top glass jar wet cells.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Other primary wet cells are the Leclanche cell, Grove cell, Bunsen cell, Chromic acid cell, Clark cell, and Weston cell.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The Leclanche cell chemistry was adapted to the first dry cells.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Wet cells are still used in automobile batteries and in industry for standby power for switchgear, telecommunication or large uninterruptible power supplies, but in many places batteries with gel cells have been used instead.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] These applications commonly use lead–acid or nickel–cadmium cells.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Molten salt batteries are primary or secondary batteries that use a molten salt as electrolyte.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] They operate at high temperatures and must be well insulated to retain heat.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A *dry cell* uses a paste electrolyte, with only enough moisture to allow current to flow.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Unlike a wet cell, a dry cell can operate in any orientation without spilling, as it contains no free liquid, making it suitable for portable equipment.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] By comparison, the first wet cells were typically fragile glass containers with lead rods hanging from the open top and needed careful handling to avoid spillage.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Lead–acid batteries did not achieve the safety and portability of the dry cell until the development of the gel battery.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A common dry cell is the zinc–carbon battery, sometimes called the dry Leclanché cell, with a nominal voltage of 1.5 volts, the same as the alkaline battery (since both use the same zinc–manganese dioxide combination).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A standard dry cell comprises a zinc anode, usually in the form of a cylindrical pot, with a carbon cathode in the form of a central rod.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The electrolyte is ammonium chloride in the form of a paste next to the zinc anode.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The remaining space between the electrolyte and carbon cathode is taken up by a second paste consisting of ammonium chloride and manganese dioxide, the latter acting as a depolariser.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In some designs, the ammonium chloride is replaced by zinc chloride.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A reserve battery can be stored unassembled (unactivated and supplying no power) for a long period (perhaps years).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] When the battery is needed, then it is assembled (e.g., by adding electrolyte); once assembled, the battery is charged and ready to work.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] For example, a battery for an electronic artillery fuze might be activated by the impact of firing a gun.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The acceleration breaks a capsule of electrolyte that activates the battery and powers the fuze's circuits.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Reserve batteries are usually designed for a short service life (seconds or minutes) after long storage (years).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A water-activated battery for oceanographic instruments or military applications becomes activated on immersion in water.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The solid-state battery is also said to have "three times the energy density", increasing its useful life in electric vehicles, for example.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] It should also be more ecologically sound since the technology uses less expensive, earth-friendly materials such as sodium extracted from seawater.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Sony has developed a biological battery that generates electricity from sugar in a way that is similar to the processes observed in living organisms.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The battery generates electricity through the use of enzymes that break down carbohydrates.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The sealed valve regulated lead–acid battery (VRLA battery) is popular in the automotive industry as a replacement for the lead–acid wet cell.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The VRLA battery uses an immobilized sulfuric acid electrolyte, reducing the chance of leakage and extending shelf life.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] VRLA batteries immobilize the electrolyte.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Other portable rechargeable batteries include several sealed "dry cell" types, that are useful in applications such as mobile phones and laptop computers.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Cells of this type (in order of increasing power density and cost) include nickel–cadmium (NiCd), nickel–zinc (NiZn), nickel–metal hydride (NiMH), and lithium-ion (Li-ion) cells.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Li-ion has by far the highest share of the dry cell rechargeable market.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] NiMH has replaced NiCd in most applications due to its higher capacity, but NiCd remains in use in power tools, two-way radios, and medical equipment.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Low self-discharge (LSD) allows secondary cells to be charged prior to shipping.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Lithium–sulfur batteries were used on the longest and highest solar-powered flight.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Batteries of all types are manufactured in consumer and industrial grades.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Standard-format batteries are inserted into battery holder in the device that uses them.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] When a device does not uses standard-format batteries, they are typically combined into a custom battery pack which holds multiple batteries in addition to features such as a battery management system and battery isolator which ensure that the batteries within are charged and discharged evenly.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Primary batteries readily available to consumers range from tiny button cells used for electric watches, to the No.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] 6 cell used for signal circuits or other long duration applications.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Secondary cells are made in very large sizes; very large batteries can power a submarine or stabilize an electrical grid and help level out peak loads.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] As of 2017, the world's largest battery was built in South Australia by Tesla.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A battery in Hebei Province, China, which can store 36 MWh of electricity was built in 2013 at a cost of $500 million.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Another large battery, composed of Ni–Cd cells, was in Fairbanks, Alaska.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] It covered 2,000 square metres (22,000 sq ft)—bigger than a football pitch—and weighed 1,300 tonnes.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] It was manufactured by ABB to provide backup power in the event of a blackout.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The battery can provide 40 MW of power for up to seven minutes.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Sodium–sulfur batteries have been used to store wind power.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A 4.4 MWh battery system that can deliver 11 MW for 25 minutes stabilizes the output of the Auwahi wind farm in Hawaii.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Many important cell properties, such as voltage, energy density, flammability, available cell constructions, operating temperature range and shelf life, are dictated by battery chemistry.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A battery's characteristics may vary over load cycle, over charge cycle, and over lifetime due to many factors including internal chemistry, current drain, and temperature.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] At low temperatures, a battery cannot deliver as much power.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] As such, in cold climates, some car owners install battery warmers, which are small electric heating pads that keep the car battery warm.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A battery's *capacity* is the amount of electric charge it can deliver at a voltage that does not drop below the specified terminal voltage.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The more electrode material contained in the cell the greater its capacity.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A small cell has less capacity than a larger cell with the same chemistry, although they develop the same open-circuit voltage.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Capacity is usually stated in ampere-hours (A·h) (mAh for small batteries).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The rated capacity of a battery is usually expressed as the product of 20 hours multiplied by the current that a new battery can consistently supply for 20 hours at 20 °C (68 °F), while remaining above a specified terminal voltage per cell.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] For example, a battery rated at 100 A·h can deliver 5 A over a 20-hour period at room temperature.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The fraction of the stored charge that a battery can deliver depends on multiple factors, including battery chemistry, the rate at which the charge is delivered (current), the required terminal voltage, the storage period, ambient temperature and other factors.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The higher the discharge rate, the lower the capacity.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] is the capacity when discharged at a rate of 1 amp.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] is the amount of time (in hours) that a battery can sustain.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Charged batteries (rechargeable or disposable) lose charge by internal self-discharge over time although not discharged, due to the presence of generally irreversible *side reactions* that consume charge carriers without producing current.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The rate of self-discharge depends upon battery chemistry and construction, typically from months to years for significant loss.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] When batteries are recharged, additional side reactions reduce capacity for subsequent discharges.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] After enough recharges, in essence all capacity is lost and the battery stops producing power.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Internal energy losses and limitations on the rate that ions pass through the electrolyte cause battery efficiency to vary.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Above a minimum threshold, discharging at a low rate delivers more of the battery's capacity than at a higher rate.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Installing batteries with varying A·h ratings changes operating time, but not device operation unless load limits are exceeded.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] High-drain loads such as digital cameras can reduce total capacity of rechargeable or disposable batteries.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] For example, a battery rated at 2 A·h for a 10- or 20-hour discharge would not sustain a current of 1 A for a full two hours as its stated capacity suggests.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The C-rate is a measure of the rate at which a battery is being charged or discharged.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] It is defined as the current through the battery divided by the theoretical current draw under which the battery would deliver its nominal rated capacity in one hour.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Because of internal resistance loss and the chemical processes inside the cells, a battery rarely delivers nameplate rated capacity in only one hour.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Typically, maximum capacity is found at a low C-rate, and charging or discharging at a higher C-rate reduces the usable life and capacity of a battery.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Manufacturers often publish datasheets with graphs showing capacity versus C-rate curves.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] C-rate is also used as a rating on batteries to indicate the maximum current that a battery can safely deliver in a circuit.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Standards for rechargeable batteries generally rate the capacity and charge cycles over a 4-hour (0.25C), 8 hour (0.125C) or longer discharge time.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Types intended for special purposes, such as in a computer uninterruptible power supply, may be rated by manufacturers for discharge periods much less than one hour (1C) but may suffer from limited cycle life.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In 2009 experimental lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO 4) battery technology provided the fastest charging and energy delivery, discharging all its energy into a load in 10 to 20 seconds.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In 2024 a prototype battery for electric cars that could charge from 10% to 80% in five minutes was demonstrated, and a Chinese company claimed that car batteries it had introduced charged 10% to 80% in 10.5 minutes—the fastest batteries available—compared to Tesla's 15 minutes to half-charge.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Battery life (or lifetime) has two meanings for rechargeable batteries but only one for non-chargeable batteries.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] It can be used to describe the length of time a device can run on a fully charged battery—this is also unambiguously termed "endurance".
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] For a rechargeable battery it may also be used for the number of charge/discharge cycles possible before the cells fail to operate satisfactorily—this is also termed "lifespan".
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The term *shelf life* is used to describe how long a battery will retain its performance between manufacture and use.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Available capacity of all batteries drops with decreasing temperature.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In contrast to most of today's batteries, the Zamboni pile, invented in 1812, offers a very long service life without refurbishment or recharge, although it can supply very little current (nanoamps).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The Oxford Electric Bell has been ringing almost continuously since 1840 on its original pair of batteries, thought to be Zamboni piles.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Disposable batteries typically lose 8–20% of their original charge per year when stored at room temperature (20–30 °C).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] This is known as the "self-discharge" rate, and is due to non-current-producing "side" chemical reactions that occur within the cell even when no load is applied.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The rate of side reactions is reduced for batteries stored at lower temperatures, although some can be damaged by freezing and storing in a fridge will not meaningfully prolong shelf life and risks damaging condensation.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Old rechargeable batteries self-discharge more rapidly than disposable alkaline batteries, especially nickel-based batteries; a freshly charged nickel cadmium (NiCd) battery loses 10% of its charge in the first 24 hours, and thereafter discharges at a rate of about 10% a month.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] However, newer low self-discharge nickel–metal hydride (NiMH) batteries and modern lithium designs display a lower self-discharge rate (but still higher than for primary batteries).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The active material on the battery plates changes chemical composition on each charge and discharge cycle; active material may be lost due to physical changes of volume, further limiting the number of times the battery can be recharged.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Most nickel-based batteries are partially discharged when purchased, and must be charged before first use.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Newer NiMH batteries are ready to be used when purchased, and have only 15% discharge in a year.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Some deterioration occurs on each charge–discharge cycle.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Degradation usually occurs because electrolyte migrates away from the electrodes or because active material detaches from the electrodes.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Low-capacity NiMH batteries (1,700–2,000 mA·h) can be charged some 1,000 times, whereas high-capacity NiMH batteries (above 2,500 mA·h) last about 500 cycles.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] NiCd batteries tend to be rated for 1,000 cycles before their internal resistance permanently increases beyond usable values.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Fast charging increases component changes, shortening battery lifespan.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] If a charger cannot detect when the battery is fully charged then overcharging is likely, damaging it.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] NiCd cells, if used in a particular repetitive manner, may show a decrease in capacity called "memory effect".
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The effect can be avoided with simple practices.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] NiMH cells, although similar in chemistry, suffer less from memory effect.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Automotive lead–acid rechargeable batteries must endure stress due to vibration, shock, and temperature range.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Because of these stresses and sulfation of their lead plates, few automotive batteries last beyond six years of regular use.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Automotive starting (SLI: *Starting, Lighting, Ignition*) batteries have many thin plates to maximize current.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In general, the thicker the plates the longer the life.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] They are typically discharged only slightly before recharge.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] "Deep-cycle" lead–acid batteries such as those used in electric golf carts have much thicker plates to extend longevity.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The main benefit of the lead–acid battery is its low cost; its main drawbacks are large size and weight for a given capacity and voltage.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Lead–acid batteries should never be discharged to below 20% of their capacity, because internal resistance will cause heat and damage when they are recharged.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Deep-cycle lead–acid systems often use a low-charge warning light or a low-charge power cut-off switch to prevent the type of damage that will shorten the battery's life.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Battery life can be extended by storing the batteries at a low temperature, as in a refrigerator or freezer, which slows the side reactions.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Such storage can extend the life of alkaline batteries by about 5%; rechargeable batteries can hold their charge much longer, depending upon type.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] To reach their maximum voltage, batteries must be returned to room temperature; discharging an alkaline battery at 250 mA at 0 °C is only half as efficient as at 20 °C.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Alkaline battery manufacturers such as Duracell do not recommend refrigerating batteries.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] A battery explosion is generally caused by misuse or malfunction, such as attempting to recharge a primary (non-rechargeable) battery, or a short circuit.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] When a battery is recharged at an excessive rate, an explosive gas mixture of hydrogen and oxygen may be produced faster than it can escape from within the battery (e.g. through a built-in vent), leading to pressure build-up and eventual bursting of the battery case.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] In extreme cases, battery chemicals may spray violently from the casing and cause injury.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] An expert summary of the problem indicates that this type uses "liquid electrolytes to transport lithium ions between the anode and the cathode.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] If a battery cell is charged too quickly, it can cause a short circuit, leading to explosions and fires".
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Car batteries are most likely to explode when a short circuit generates very large currents.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Such batteries produce hydrogen, which is very explosive, when they are overcharged (because of electrolysis of the water in the electrolyte).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] During normal use, the amount of overcharging is usually very small and generates little hydrogen, which dissipates quickly.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] However, when "jump starting" a car, the high current can cause the rapid release of large volumes of hydrogen, which can be ignited explosively by a nearby spark, e.g. when disconnecting a jumper cable.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Overcharging (attempting to charge a battery beyond its electrical capacity) can also lead to a battery explosion, in addition to leakage or irreversible damage.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] It may also cause damage to the charger or device in which the overcharged battery is later used.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Disposing of a battery via incineration may cause an explosion as steam builds up within the sealed case.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Many battery chemicals are corrosive, poisonous or both.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] If leakage occurs, either spontaneously or through accident, the chemicals released may be dangerous.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] For example, disposable batteries often use a zinc "can" both as a reactant and as the container to hold the other reagents.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] If this kind of battery is over-discharged, the reagents can emerge through the cardboard and plastic that form the remainder of the container.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The active chemical leakage can then damage or disable the equipment that the batteries power.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] For this reason, many electronic device manufacturers recommend removing the batteries from devices that will not be used for extended periods of time.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Many types of batteries employ toxic materials such as lead, mercury, and cadmium as an electrode or electrolyte.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] When each battery reaches end of life it must be disposed of to prevent environmental damage.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Batteries are one form of electronic waste (e-waste).
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] E-waste recycling services recover toxic substances, which can then be used for new batteries.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Of the nearly three billion batteries purchased annually in the United States, about 179,000 tons end up in landfills across the country.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Batteries may be harmful or fatal if swallowed.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Small button cells can be swallowed, in particular by young children.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] While in the digestive tract, the battery's electrical discharge may lead to tissue damage; such damage is occasionally serious and can lead to death.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Ingested disk batteries do not usually cause problems unless they become lodged in the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The most common place for disk batteries to become lodged is the esophagus, resulting in clinical sequelae.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] Batteries that successfully traverse the esophagus are unlikely to lodge elsewhere.
[src:batteryless-radio/battery-electricity] The likelihood that a disk battery will lodge in the esophagus is a function of the patient's age and the size of the battery.
